Document Classification

Aim: This notebook compares the performance of the Naive Bayes classifier to a neural net for document classification after feature transformation.
Final results show significant increase in performance metrics when using a shallow neural net compared to a Naive Bayes classifier.

Data: The data is obtained from the training set of the Kaggle competition, Coleridge Initiative - Show Us the Data and consists of published research articles (documents) and their labels, which are datasets cited by the articles. Since the public test set is limited to only 4 documents, the focus will be on the training set, containing 19,661 records.

The aim of the competition was to create a model capable of identifying datasets cited in research papers. The inherent difficulty of this task has to do with the infinitely large number of datasets in the wild that any given article can cite, while having a limited number of datasets (labels) for training a model.

Unlike the competition, the purpose here is to simply create a classifier on existing dataset labels and accurately classify new documents that contain one of such labels. Hence, we will evaluate the performance of a baseline classifier (Naive Bayes) to a neural net by spliting the train dataset from the competition to train, validation and test sets of our own.

This notebook is structured as follows:

  1. Data preprocessing and exploratory data analysis
  2. Feature transformation using TFIDF and label encoding
  3. Evaluating of Naive Bayes classifier
  4. Evaluation of neural net classifier
  5. Conclusion

In [2]:
def json_to_text(filename, directory_path):
    """convert json file into concatenated text data."""
    content = list()
    file_path = os.path.join(directory_path, filename + '.json')
    with open(file_path, 'r') as f:
        json_file = json.load(f)
        for data in json_file:
            content.append(data.get('text'))
    return ''.join(content)

def process_text(text):
    """convert text to alphanumeric lowercase characters."""
    text = re.sub('[^A-Za-z0-9]+', ' ', str(text).lower()).strip()
    return text

def convert_sparse_matrix_to_sparse_tensor(x):
    """convert scikit-learn sparse matrix into TensorFlow tensors."""
    coo = x.tocoo()
    indices = np.mat([coo.row, coo.col]).transpose()
    return tf.sparse.reorder(tf.SparseTensor(indices, coo.data, coo.shape))

def jaccard_coef(str1, str2):
    """return the Jaccard similarity coefficient of two strings.
    Algorithm provided by competition."""
    a = set(str1.lower().split())
    b = set(str2.lower().split())
    c = a.intersection(b)
    return float(len(c)) / (len(a) + len(b) - len(c))

Encode our features using TFIDF:
Just as we have encoded the label for our data, we need to convert our features represented by strings in each document to a numerical form to be able to utilize machine learning models. One way to do this is through term-frequency inverse document-frequency (TFIDF).
TFIDF is an improvement over the bag-of-words method, where in addition to counting the frequencies of words in each document, we obtain a better sense of how important a word is over the entire corpus of documents by multiplying the frequency with a weighting scheme called inverse document frequency. This will result in a sparse matrix, where most values are zero. Each column will represent a word with rows containing the TFIDF score in each document for that word. Thankfully, these TFIDF matrices can be stored in memory optimally using one of Pythons scientific libraries such as SciPy.

Convert tfidf matrixes into tensorflow tensors:

Create the layers of the neural net:

In [71]:
best_model_file_name = 'nlp_model.h5'
input_dim = x_test.shape[1]
output_dim = len(np.unique(y_train)) + 1
model = Sequential()
model.add(Dense(100, input_dim=input_dim, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(50, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(output_dim, activation='softmax'))
model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
mdl_es = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=50, verbose=1, mode='min')
mdl_mc = ModelCheckpoint(best_model_file_name, save_best_only=True, monitor='val_loss', mode='min', verbose=1)

Fit the model

model.fit(x_train_tf, encoded_y_train, epochs=10, validation_data=(x_val_tf, encoded_y_val), verbose=1,
          callbacks=[mdl_es, mdl_mc])

Conclusion


This simple experiment has shown the superiority of deep learning over classical machine learning models such as Naive Bayes. Although the above neural net was shallow and only ran for ten epochs, we were still able to obtain much higher accuracy and mcc values. It took approximately 10 minutes to complete fitting the neural net without using any GPUs. Moreover, if we were to add more layers and neurons, tune the parameters and hyperparameters, and train longer, we could potentially improve the performance even more.
